Setup Kubernetes Cluster normal way:

The configuration of the overall K8s cluster is divided into three major segments: 
1. configuring the master node, 
2. configuring two worker nodes, and possible issues. 

The below section lists the common configuration required on all three nodes and illustrates the master configuration along the steps.

Step 1: Set Hostname and Update Hosts file
# hostnamectl set-hostname k8s-cp01
# hostnamectl set-hostname k8s-w01
# hostnamectl set-hostname k8s-w02

# vi /etc/hosts
192.168.122.156  k8s-cp01.kubernetes.local server.kubernetes.local k8s-cp01 server
192.168.122.221 k8s-w01.kubernetes.local k8s-w01
192.168.122.45 k8s-w02.kubernetes.local k8s-w02 

192.168.122.156  k8s-cp01
192.168.122.221 k8s-w01
192.168.122.45 k8s-w02

Step 2: Disable Swap Space on Each Node and verify cgroups
# swapoff -a
# sed -i '/ swap / s/^\(.*\)$/#\1/g' /etc/fstab

# stat -fc %T /sys/fs/cgroup/
For cgroup v2, the output is cgroup2fs. ==> It should be grpup v2, if not, migrate to V2 by following steps suggest by OS OEM.
For cgroup v1, the output is tmpfs.

Deprecation of cgroup v1: FEATURE STATE: Kubernetes v1.35 [deprecated]. 

Step 3: Adjust SELinux and Firewall Rules for Kubernetes
# setenforce 0
# vi  /etc/selinux/config or /etc/sysconfig/selinux 
SELINUX=disabled

On the master node, allow following ports in the firewall.
# firewall-cmd --permanent --add-port={6443,2379,2380,10250,10251,10252,10257,10259,179}/tcp
# firewall-cmd --permanent --add-port=4789/udp
# firewall-cmd --reload

**** Port Details *****
These firewall rules are typically opened on Kubernetes control-plane (master) nodes. Each port serves a specific Kubernetes component.
Port	Protocol	Component	Purpose
6443	TCP	kube-apiserver	Main Kubernetes API endpoint. Workers, kubectl, controllers, and schedulers connect here.
2379	TCP	etcd	Client port for reading/writing cluster state to etcd.
2380	TCP	etcd	Peer communication between etcd members in a multi-master cluster.
10250	TCP	kubelet	Used by the API server to communicate with kubelets on nodes.
10251	TCP	kube-scheduler (older versions)	Scheduler metrics/health endpoint. Often unused in newer Kubernetes versions.
10252	TCP	kube-controller-manager (older versions)	Controller-manager metrics/health endpoint. Often unused in newer versions.
10257	TCP	kube-controller-manager	Secure controller-manager endpoint.
10259	TCP	kube-scheduler	Secure scheduler endpoint.
179	TCP	Calico BGP	Used when Calico operates in BGP mode for route exchange. Not required for all CNIs.
4789	UDP	VXLAN	Overlay network tunnel used by Calico VXLAN, Flannel VXLAN, etc.

On the Worker Nodes, allow beneath ports in the firewall,

$ sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-port={179,10250,30000-32767}/tcp
$ sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-port=4789/udp
$ sudo firewall-cmd --reload

**** Port Details *****
These firewall ports are commonly opened on Kubernetes worker nodes to allow pod networking, node management, and external access to services.

Port	Protocol	Component	Purpose
179	TCP	Calico BGP	Route exchange between nodes when Calico is running in BGP mode.
10250	TCP	kubelet	Allows the API server to communicate with the kubelet on the worker node.
30000-32767	TCP	NodePort Services	Exposes Kubernetes services externally through node IPs.
4789	UDP	VXLAN	Overlay network tunnel used by Calico VXLAN, Flannel VXLAN, etc.

Step 4: Add Kernel Modules and Parameters
# vi /etc/modules-load.d/containerd.conf
overlay
br_netfilter

# modprobe overlay
# modprobe br_netfilter

Next, add the following kernel parameters, create a file and with following content,

# vi /etc/sysctl.d/k8s.conf
net.bridge.bridge-nf-call-iptables  = 1
net.ipv4.ip_forward                 = 1
net.bridge.bridge-nf-call-ip6tables = 1

Now add these parameters by running below command

$ sudo sysctl --system

Kubernetes networking components need the kernel to:

Forward packets between interfaces (ip_forward=1).
Allow bridged traffic to be inspected by iptables (bridge-nf-call-* = 1).

Step 5: Install Conatinerd Runtime
Kubernetes requires a container runtime, and one of the most popular choices is containerd. But It is not available in the default package repositories of Rocky Linux or AlmaLinux, so add the following docker repo on all the nodes.

# dnf config-manager --add-repo https://download.docker.com/linux/centos/docker-ce.repo
# sudo dnf install containerd.io -y

Modifying the system_cgroup
On Linux, control groups (cgroups) manage allocated resources for processes. The kubelet and container runtime interact with cgroups to enforce resource management for pods, setting CPU/memory requests and limits. They must use the same cgroup driver and configuration.

Two cgroup drivers exist:
cgroupfs
systemd.

The cgroupfs driver is the default in the kubelet, interfacing directly with the cgroup filesystem. However, it’s not recommended with systemd as the init system due to potential conflicts. Instead, when using systemd, the systemd cgroup driver is preferred. Systemd acts as a cgroup manager, allocating a cgroup per systemd unit. This integration avoids the instability that can occur when using cgroupfs alongside systemd.Configure containerd so that it will use systemdcgroup, execute the following commands on each node.

# containerd config default | sudo tee /etc/containerd/config.toml >/dev/null 2>&1
# sudo sed -i 's/SystemdCgroup \= false/SystemdCgroup \= true/g' /etc/containerd/config.toml

# systemctl restart containerd
# sudo systemctl enable containerd

Step 6: Install Kubernetes tools

Kubernetes tools like Kubeadm, kubectl and kubelet are not available in the default package repositories of Rocky Linux 9 or AlmaLinux 9. So, to install these tools, add the following repository on all the nodes.

# This overwrites any existing configuration in /etc/yum.repos.d/kubernetes.repo
cat <<EOF | sudo tee /etc/yum.repos.d/kubernetes.repo
[kubernetes]
name=Kubernetes
baseurl=https://pkgs.k8s.io/core:/stable:/v1.35/rpm/
enabled=1
gpgcheck=1
gpgkey=https://pkgs.k8s.io/core:/stable:/v1.35/rpm/repodata/repomd.xml.key
EOF


